{{Campaignbox Croatian War of Independence}}
{{Campaignbox Bosnian War}}

'''Operation Winter '94''' ({{lang-hr|Operacija Zima '94}}) was a joint military offensive of the [[Croatian Army]] (HV) and the [[Croatian Defence Council]] (HVO) fought in southwestern [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]] between 29 November and 24 December 1994. The operation formed part of the [[Croatian War of Independence]] and the [[Bosnian War]] fought between Bosnia and Herzegovina, [[Croatia]] and two unrecognized para-states proclaimed by [[Croatian Serbs]] and [[Bosnian Serbs]]. Both para-states were supported by the [[Yugoslav People's Army]] (JNA) and [[Republic of Serbia (1990-2006)|Serbia]]. The JNA pulled out in 1992, but transferred much of its equipment to the Bosnian Serb and Croatian Serb forces as it withdrew.

Operation Winter '94 was the first in a series of successful advances made by the HV and the HVO in or near the [[Livanjsko field]], an elongated flat-bottomed valley surrounded by hills. The region was formally controlled by the HVO, but the HV contributed a substantial force, including commanding officers. The attacks were primarily designed to draw the [[Army of Republika Srpska]] (VRS) away from the [[Siege of Bihać|besieged city of Bihać]]. The secondary objective was threatening the single direct supply route between [[Drvar]] in the Bosnian Serb [[Republika Srpska]] and [[Knin]], the capital of the Croatian Serb [[Republic of Serbian Krajina]] (RSK).

Operation Winter '94 pushed back the front line of the VRS by about {{convert|20|km|abbr=off}}, capturing much of the Livanjsko field. The attack failed to achieve its primary objective but it brought the Croatian forces within striking distance of the Drvar–Knin road. Operation Winter '94 was followed by Operation Leap&nbsp;1 (''Operacija Skok&nbsp;1'') on 7 April 1995, which improved HV positions on [[Dinara|Mount Dinara]] on the southern rim of the field, dominating the area around the RSK capital. The Croatian forces renewed their advance with Operation Leap&nbsp;2 between 4 and 10 June, allowing them to directly threaten [[Bosansko Grahovo]] on the Drvar–Knin road, and to secure the remainder of the valley. The improved Croatian dispositions around Livanjsko field provided a springboard for further offensive action on this front during [[Operation Summer&nbsp;'95]].

==Background==
{{main|Croatian War of Independence|Bosnian War}}
[[File:Bihac Pocket 1994-1995.svg|250px|thumb|right|alt=Multicoloured map of Bihać pocket and adjacent areas in Croatia and Bosnia and Herzegovina|Map of Bihać pocket:<br>Areas in Croatia controlled by:<br>{{legend inline|#ff7f74|[[Army of the Republic of Serb Krajina|ARSK]]}}, {{legend inline|#fefee9|[[Croatian Army|HV]]}}<br>Areas in Bosnia and Herzegovina controlled by:<br>{{legend inline|#e9afaf|[[Army of Republika Srpska|VRS]]}}, {{legend inline|#c83737|ARSK}}, {{legend inline|#b3ff80|[[Army of the Republic of Bosnia and Herzegovina|ARBiH]]}}, {{legend inline|#5aa02c|[[Autonomous Province of Western Bosnia|APWB]]}}<br>1 – Bihać, 2 – Cazin, 3 – Velika Kladuša, 4 – Bosanska Krupa, 5 – Bosanski Petrovac, 6 – Drvar, 7 – Sanski Most, 8 – Prijedor, 9 – Udbina, 10 – Korenica, 11 – Slunj, 12 – Vojnić, 13 – Glina, 14 – Dvor, 15 – Kostajnica, 16 – Petrinja, 17 – Sisak, 18 – Karlovac, 19 – Ogulin, 20 – Gospić, 21 – Otočac]]

Following the [[Croatian parliamentary election, 1990|1990 electoral defeat]] of the government of the [[Socialist Republic of Croatia]], ethnic tensions grew. The [[Yugoslav People's Army]] (''Jugoslovenska Narodna Armija'' – JNA) confiscated Croatia's [[Territorial Defense Forces (Yugoslavia)|Territorial Defence]] (''Teritorijalna obrana'') weapons to minimize resistance.<ref>{{harvnb|Hoare|2010|p=117}}</ref> On 17 August, the tensions escalated into an [[Log Revolution|open revolt]] by [[Serbs of Croatia|Croatian Serbs]],<ref name=Hoare118>{{harvnb|Hoare|2010|p=118}}</ref> centred on the predominantly Serb-populated areas of the [[Dalmatia]]n hinterland around [[Knin]],<ref>{{harvnb|The New York Times|19 August 1990}}</ref> parts of the [[Lika]], [[Kordun]], [[Banovina (region)|Banovina]] and [[eastern Croatia]].<ref name=MarticICTY>{{harvnb|ICTY|12 June 2007}}</ref> This was followed by two unsuccessful attempts by [[Republic of Serbia (1990–2006)|Serbia]], supported by [[Socialist Republic of Montenegro|Montenegro]] and Serbia's provinces of [[Vojvodina]] and [[Autonomous Province of Kosovo and Metohija|Kosovo]] to obtain the [[Yugoslav Presidency]]'s approval of a JNA operation to disarm Croatian security forces in January 1991.<ref>{{harvnb|Hoare|2010|pp=118–119}}</ref> After a bloodless skirmish between Serb insurgents and [[Croatian special police order of battle in 1991–95|Croatian special police]] in March,<ref>{{harvnb|Ramet|2006|pp=384–385}}</ref> the JNA, supported by Serbia and its allies, asked the federal Presidency declare a [[state of emergency]] and grant the JNA wartime powers. The request was denied on 15 March, and the JNA came under control of Serbian President [[Slobodan Milošević]]. Milošević, preferring a campaign to expand Serbia rather than preservation of Yugoslavia, publicly threatened to replace the JNA with a Serbian army and declared that he no longer recognized the authority of the federal Presidency.<ref name=Hoare119>{{harvnb|Hoare|2010|p=119}}</ref> By the end of March, the conflict had escalated into the [[Croatian War of Independence]].<ref>{{harvnb|The New York Times|3 March 1991}}</ref> The JNA stepped in, increasingly supporting the Croatian Serb insurgents and preventing [[Law enforcement in Croatia|Croatian police]] from intervening.<ref name=Hoare119/> In early April, the leaders of the Croatian Serb revolt declared their intention to integrate the area under their control with Serbia. The Government of Croatia viewed this declaration as an attempt to secede.<ref>{{harvnb|The New York Times|2 April 1991}}</ref>

In May, the Croatian government responded by forming the [[Croatian National Guard]] (''Zbor narodne garde'' – ZNG),<ref name=EECIS272>{{harvnb|EECIS|1999|pp=272–278}}</ref> but its development was hampered by a [[United Nations]] (UN) [[United Nations Security Council Resolution 713|arms embargo]] introduced in September.<ref>{{harvnb|The Independent|10 October 1992}}</ref> On 8 October, Croatia declared independence from Yugoslavia,<ref>{{harvnb|Narodne novine|8 October 1991}}</ref> and a month later the ZNG was renamed the Croatian Army (''Hrvatska vojska'' - HV).<ref name=EECIS272/> Late 1991 saw the fiercest fighting of the Croatian War of Independence, culminating in the [[Siege of Dubrovnik]]<ref>{{harvnb|Bjelajac|Žunec|2009|pp=249–250}}</ref> and the [[Battle of Vukovar]].<ref>{{harvnb|The New York Times|18 November 1991}}</ref> A campaign of [[ethnic cleansing]] then began in the RSK, and most non-Serbs were expelled.<ref>{{harvnb|Department of State|31 January 1994}}</ref><ref name=UNCHR>{{harvnb|ECOSOC|17 November 1993|loc=Section J, points 147 & 150}}</ref> In January 1992, an agreement to implement the [[Vance plan|peace plan]] negotiated by UN special envoy [[Cyrus Vance]] was signed by Croatia, the JNA and the UN.<ref name="NYTimes-Jan3-Ceasefire">{{harvnb|The New York Times|3 January 1992}}</ref> As a result, the [[United Nations Protection Force]] (UNPROFOR) deployed to maintain the ceasefire,<ref>{{harvnb|Los Angeles Times|29 January 1992}}</ref> and the JNA was scheduled to retreat to Bosnia and Herzegovina, where further conflict was anticipated.<ref name="NYTimes-Jan3-Ceasefire"/> Despite the peace arrangement requiring an immediate withdrawal of JNA personnel and equipment from Croatia, it remained on Croatian territory for seven to eight months. When its troops eventually withdrew, the JNA left its equipment to the [[Army of the Republic of Serb Krajina]] (ARSK).<ref>{{harvnb|Armatta|2010|p=197}}</ref> The January ceasefire also allowed the JNA to maintain its positions in East and West [[Slavonia]] that were on the brink of military collapse following a [[Operation Orkan 91|Croatian counteroffensive]], which reclaimed 60% of the JNA-held territory in West Slavonia by the time the ceasefire went into effect.<ref>{{harvnb|Hoare|2010|p=123}}</ref> However, Serbia continued to support the RSK.<ref>{{harvnb|Thompson|2012|p=417}}</ref> The HV restored small areas around Dubrovnik to Croatian control<ref>{{harvnb|The New York Times|15 July 1992}}</ref> and during [[Operation Maslenica]] it recaptured some areas of Lika and northern Dalmatia.<ref>{{harvnb|The New York Times|24 January 1993}}</ref> Croatian population centres continued to be intermittently targeted by artillery, missiles and air raids throughout the war.<ref name=MarticICTY/><ref>{{harvnb|ECOSOC|17 November 1993|loc=Section K, point 161}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|The New York Times|13 September 1993}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|The Seattle Times|16 July 1992}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|The New York Times|17 August 1995}}</ref>

On 9 January 1992, a Bosnian Serb state was declared, ahead of the 29 February{{spaced ndash}}1 March referendum on the independence of Bosnia and Herzegovina{{mdash}}later cited as a pretext for the [[Bosnian War]]).<ref name=Ramet382>{{harvnb|Ramet|2006|p=382}}</ref> The Bosnian Serb state was later renamed [[Republika Srpska]].<ref name=Ramet428>{{harvnb|Ramet|2006|p=428}}</ref> As the JNA withdrew from Croatia it started to transform into a Bosnian Serb army,<ref name=Ramet382/> handing over its weapons, equipment and 55,000 troops. The process was completed in May, when the Bosnian Serb army became the [[Army of Republika Srpska]] (''Vojska Republike Srpske'' – VRS).<ref name=Ramet429>{{harvnb|Ramet|2006|p=429}}</ref> It was faced by the [[Croatian Defence Council]] (HVO), established in April,<ref>{{harvnb|Eriksson|Kostić|2013|pp=26–27}}</ref> and the Bosnia and Herzegovina TO{{mdash}}renamed the [[Army of the Republic of Bosnia and Herzegovina]] (''Armija Republike Bosne i Hercegovine'' – ARBiH) in May.<ref name=Ramet429/> Formal establishment of these forces was preceded by the first armed clashes in the country as the Bosnian Serbs set up barricades in [[Sarajevo]] and elsewhere on 1&nbsp;March and the situation rapidly escalated. Bosnian Serb artillery began shelling [[Bosanski Brod]] by the end of March,<ref>{{harvnb|Ramet|2006|p=427}}</ref> and Sarajevo was first shelled on 4&nbsp;April.<ref name=Ramet428/> By the end of 1992, the VRS held 70% of Bosnia and Herzegovina,<ref name=Ramet433>{{harvnb|Ramet|2006|p=433}}</ref> following a large-scale campaign of conquest and ethnic cleansing backed by military and financial support from the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia.<ref name=Bieber>{{harvnb|Bieber|2010|p=313}}</ref> The Bosnian War gradually evolved into a three-sided conflict. The initial [[Agreement on Friendship and Cooperation between Bosnia and Herzegovina and Croatia|ARBiH–HVO alliance]] soon deteriorated as the forces became rivals for control of parts of the country. Ethnic tensions escalated from apparently insignificant harassment in July,<ref name=Ramet429/> to an open [[Croat–Bosniak War]] by October 1992.<ref name=Ramet433/> The [[Bosnian Croat]] authorities, organized in the [[Herzeg-Bosnia]] territory, were intent on attaching the region to Croatia.<ref name=Bieber/> This was incompatible with Bosniak aspirations for a unitary state.<ref>{{harvnb|Burg|Shoup|2000|p=68}}</ref>

==Prelude==
In November 1994, the [[Siege of Bihać]] entered a critical stage as the VRS and the ARSK came close to capturing the town from the Bosniak-dominated ARBiH. [[Bihać]] was seen as a strategic area by the international community. It was thought that its capture by Serb forces would intensify the war, widening the division between the United States on one side and France and the United Kingdom on the other (advocating different approaches to the area's preservation),<ref>{{harvnb|The Independent|27 November 1994}}</ref> and feared that Bihać would become the worst humanitarian disaster of the war.<ref>{{harvnb|Halberstam|2003|pp=284–286}}</ref> Furthermore, denying Bihać to the Serbs was strategically important to Croatia.<ref>{{harvnb|Hodge|2006|p=104}}</ref> Brigadier General [[Krešimir Ćosić (politician)|Krešimir Ćosić]] expected the VRS and the ARSK would threaten Karlovac and Sisak once they captured Bihać, while Chief of Croatia's General Staff General [[Janko Bobetko]] believed the fall of Bihać would represent an end to Croatia's war effort.<ref name="JL-Winter">{{harvnb|Jutarnji list|9 December 2007}}</ref>

Following a US military strategy endorsed by President [[Bill Clinton]] in February 1993,<ref>{{harvnb|Woodward|2010|p=432}}</ref> the [[Washington Agreement]] was signed in March 1994. This ended the Croat–Bosniak War,<ref name="JL-Winter"/> abolished Herzeg-Bosnia,<ref>{{harvnb|Jutarnji list|16 September 2006}}</ref> established the [[Federation of Bosnia and Herzegovina]] and forged the ARBiH–HVO alliance against the VRS.<ref name="Ramet 2006 439">{{harvnb|Ramet|2006|p=439}}</ref> In addition, a series of meetings between US and Croatian officials were held in [[Zagreb]] and [[Washington, D.C.]]<ref name="JL-Winter"/> In November 1994, the United States unilaterally ended the arms embargo against Bosnia and Herzegovina<ref>{{harvnb|Bono|2003|p=107}}</ref>{{mdash}}in effect allowing the HV to supply itself as arms shipments flowed through Croatia.<ref name="Ramet 2006 439"/> In a meeting held on 29 November 1994, Croatian representatives proposed to attack Serb-held territory from [[Livno]] in Bosnia and Herzegovina to draw off part of the force besieging Bihać and prevent its capture by the Serbs. U.S. officials made no response to the proposal. Operation Winter&nbsp;'94 was ordered the same day; it was to be carried out by the HV and the HVO{{mdash}}the main military forces of the Bosnian Croats.<ref name="JL-Winter"/>

Operation Winter&nbsp;'94 became feasible after the HVO captured [[Kupres]] (north of the [[Livanjsko field]]) in [[Operation Cincar]] on 3 November 1994, securing the right flank of the planned advance northwest of Livno. The HVO and the ARBiH advanced towards Kupres, in the first military effort coordinated between them since the Washington Agreement.<ref>{{harvnb|CIA|2002|pp=242–243}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|CIA|2002|loc=note 227/V}}</ref>

==Order of battle==
The HV deployed up to 9,000 troops on rotation through the area during the Operation Winter&nbsp;'94, keeping approximately 3,000–4,000 troops on the ground at any time,<ref>{{harvnb|CIA|2002|loc=note 304/V}}</ref> and the HVO fielded an additional 2,000–3,000. The defending force of the VRS 2nd Krajina Corps consisted of about 3,500 soldiers, spread along the {{convert|55|km|adj=on}} front line.<ref name=BB250>{{harvnb|CIA|2002|p=250}}</ref> The Bosnian Serb defenders were commanded by [[Colonel]] Radivoje Tomanić.<ref name=SVK612>{{harvnb|SVK|6 December 1994}}</ref> The attacking force was nominally controlled by the HVO, with Major General [[Tihomir Blaškić]] in overall command of the attack.<ref name=BB250/> The HV General Staff appointed Major General [[Ante Gotovina]] as commander of the [[Split, Croatia|Split]] Corps and commanding officer of the HV units.<ref>{{harvnb|Nova TV|16 November 2012}}</ref> The Croatian forces were organized into operational groups (OG). OG [[Sinj]] was located on the left flank (on Croatian soil),<ref name=SD301111>{{harvnb|Slobodna Dalmacija|30 November 2011}}</ref> OG Livno in the centre and OG Kupres on the right flank of the attack in Bosnia and Herzegovina. OG Kupres mainly consisted of HVO units, while the bulk of the OG Sinj and OG Livno was made up of HV troops.<ref name=BB250/>

