==Timeline and results==
[[File:Map 40 - Bosnia - Livno Valley November-December 1994.jpg|thumb|350px|left|alt=Military map of Operation Winter '94|Map of Operation Winter '94]]

Operation Winter&nbsp;'94 began on 29 November 1994 in heavy snow and temperatures of {{convert|-20|C|abbr=off}}. One hundred and thirty soldiers from the HV&nbsp;126th Home Guard Regiment commanded by Brigadier [[Ante Kotromanović]] infiltrated behind VRS positions on the left flank of the front line<ref name=SD301111/> (head of the initial north-west advance along the Livanjsko field and [[Dinara|Mount Dinara]], with most of the HV troops commanded by Gotovina<ref name=BB250251>{{harvnb|CIA|2002|pp=250–251}}</ref> against the VRS 9th&nbsp;Light Infantry Brigade. By 3 December, the advance gained {{convert|4|to|5|km|abbr=off}} around [[Donji Rujani]], followed by a brief stabilization of the newly established line of contact.<ref name=RSK94>{{harvnb|RSK|23 December 1994}}</ref>

The advance was resumed on 6 December as the HV 4th&nbsp;Guards Brigade and the 126th&nbsp;Home Guard Regiment gradually pushing back the VRS 9th&nbsp;Light Infantry Brigade towards Bosansko Grahovo.<ref name=RSK94/> In more than a week of gradual advance, the force penetrated the VRS defences by {{convert|10|to|12|km|abbr=off}} in the general direction of Bosansko Grahovo. The HVO units on the right flank of the attack made little progress towards [[Glamoč]], and were faced with a determined VRS defence.<ref name=BB250251/> By 11 December, the VRS 9th Light Infantry Brigade had sustained losses sufficient to demoralize the unit, further complicating the battlefield situation for the VRS as the civilian population began to leave Glamoč. The civilian evacuation was nearly complete by 16 December; on that day valuables were removed from churches and monasteries in the VRS-held territory near the front line, although there was no immediate threat to them. On 23 December, the Croatian forces reached [[Crni Lug (Bosansko Grahovo)|Crni Lug]] at the northwest rim of the Livanjsko field, forcing the VRS 9th Light Infantry Brigade to withdraw to more defensible positions.<ref name=RSK94/> On 24 December, the VRS withdrawal was complete and the operation ended.<ref name=BB251>{{harvnb|CIA|2002|p=251}}</ref> In response to the reversals they had suffered, the VRS brought two brigades and two battalions from the 1st Krajina Corps, the Herzegovina Corps and the East Bosnian Corps to secure its defences in the Glamoč and Bosansko Grahovo areas and encourage civilians to return.<ref name=Marijan47>{{harvnb|Marijan|2007|p=47}}</ref>

After nearly a month of fighting, the Croatian forces had advanced by about {{convert|20|km|abbr=off}} and had captured approximately {{convert|200|km2|abbr=off}} of territory northwest of Livno.<ref name=BB251/> The VRS had been pushed back to a line approximately {{convert|19|km|abbr=off}} south-east of Bosansko Grahovo.<ref>{{harvnb|Marijan|2007|p=46}}</ref> The HV and the HVO sustained losses of 29 killed, 19 seriously wounded and 39 slightly injured troops. Three soldiers were captured by the VRS, but they were later released in a prisoner-of-war exchange.<ref name=SD301111/> In a report following Operation Winter&nbsp;'94, the VRS 2nd&nbsp;Krajina Corps reported serious manpower shortages and 20% casualties.<ref>{{harvnb|Marijan|2007|p=241}}</ref> After the operation, ARSK deployed to Glamoč and Bosansko Grahovo area to assist the VRS in continued skirmishes against the Croatian forces in the area. Croatian troops retained most of the ground, representing a [[Salients, re-entrants and pockets#Salient|salient]] to the north-west of Livno, gained during the winter offensive.<ref name=BB295>{{harvnb|CIA|2002|p=295}}</ref> The lull in fighting continued until mid-March 1995.<ref name=BB296>{{harvnb|CIA|2002|p=296}}</ref>

