| combatant1  = {{flag|Croatia}}<br>{{flag|Republic of Bosnia and Herzegovina|1992}} 
* [[File:Flag of Croatian Defence Council.svg|22px|border|Croatian Defence Council|alt=|link=]] HVO
| combatant2  = {{flag|Republika Srpska}}<br>{{flag|Serbian Krajina}}
| commander1  = {{flagicon|Croatia}} [[Janko Bobetko]]<br>{{flagicon|Croatia}} [[Ante Gotovina]]
| commander2  = {{flagicon|Republika Srpska}} [[Ratko Mladić]]<br>{{flagicon|Republika Srpska}} Radivoje Tomanić<br>{{flagicon|Serbian Krajina}} [[Milan Čeleketić]]
| strength1   = 5,000
| strength2   = 3,500
}}
Operation Leap&nbsp;2, or Operation Jump&nbsp;2<ref name=MORH17/> (''Operacija Skok&nbsp;2'') was a joint operation of the HV and the HVO aimed primarily at capturing the main mountain pass out of the Livanjsko field on the Livno-Bosansko Grahovo road, and the high ground overlooking Glamoč, to give the Croatian forces good positions from which to advance further into VRS-held territory. It was thought that the attack might also force the VRS to withdraw some of its forces that had been [[Battle of Orašje|attacking the Orašje pocket]] since May. Gotovina planned a two-stage, two-pronged advance towards the main objectives and an auxiliary attack on ARSK-held territory south-west of the salient. In the first stage of the operation, the attacking forces were tasked with capturing the village of Crni Lug and the southern part of the pass,<ref name=BB299>{{harvnb|CIA|2002|p=299}}</ref> while the second stage was planned to capture the {{convert|1872|m|adj=on}} [[Šator|Mount Šator]] and the Crvena Zemlja ridge to the north,<ref name=Marijan4849>{{harvnb|Marijan|2007|pp=48–49}}</ref> blocking the Bosansko Grahovo-Glamoč road and making Glamoč difficult to resupply.<ref name=BB299/>

The Croatian forces fielded approximately 5,000&nbsp;troops, spearheaded by the HV 4th&nbsp;Guards Brigade<ref name=BB299/> and supported by the [[1st Croatian Guards Brigade|1st&nbsp;Croatian Guards Brigade]] (''1. hrvatski gardijski zdrug'' - HGZ), the 1st&nbsp;Battalion of the [[1st Guards Brigade (Croatia)|1st&nbsp;Guards Brigade]], the 3rd&nbsp;Battalion of the 126th&nbsp;Home Guard Regiment of the HV, the HVO 3rd&nbsp;Guards Brigade and the Bosnian Croat special police.<ref name=Marijan4849/><ref name=BBN94>{{harvnb|CIA|2002|loc=note 94}}</ref> The opposing forces comprised approximately 3,000&nbsp;troops in three light infantry brigades of the VRS 2nd&nbsp;Krajina Corps and a 500-strong ARSK composite ''Vijuga'' [[Battlegroup (army)|battlegroup]], assembled by the ARSK 7th&nbsp;North Dalmatian Corps.<ref name=BB300>{{harvnb|CIA|2002|p=300}}</ref> The ''Vijuga'' battlegroup was deployed with elements of the ARSK 1st Light Infantry Brigade in the Croatia-Bosnia and Herzegovina border zone on Dinara. The VRS formations consisted of the 3rd&nbsp;and the 9th&nbsp;Light Infantry Brigades in the Bosansko Grahovo area and the 5th&nbsp;Light Infantry Brigade in the Glamoč zone. The reinforcements that had been sent to the area in the aftermath of Operation Winter '94 were broken up and used to reinforce the VRS brigades.<ref>{{harvnb|CIA|2002|loc=note 95}}</ref>

Operation Leap&nbsp;2 began on 4 June with the advance of the HV 4th&nbsp;Guards Brigade. HVO troops took Crni Lug and the mountain pass en route to Bosansko Grahovo, the operation's chief objective.<ref name=BB300/> Its left flank, in the border area, was protected by the 3rd&nbsp;Battalion of the 126th&nbsp;Home Guard Regiment and the Tactical Sniper Company attached to the HV Split Corps.<ref name=BBN94/> The VRS counterattacked on 6–7 June, trying to roll back the 4th&nbsp;Guards Brigade. The VRS push failed, as did its efforts to contain the advance with close air support and [[M-87 Orkan]] rockets. On 6 June (the same day as the VRS counterattack), the second phase of Operation Leap&nbsp;2 began. The 1st&nbsp;Battalion of the 1st&nbsp;Guards Brigade supported by the HV 264th Reconnaissance Sabotage Company and elements of the HV 1st HGZ advanced north from Livno, capturing the high ground near Glamoč and blocking the Bosansko Grahovo-Glamoč road by 10 June.<ref name=BB300/> To pin down the VRS on the right flank of the attack, the HVO 2nd Guards Brigade attacked VRS positions on Golija Mountain south-west of Glamoč.<ref name=BBN94/>

Operations Leap&nbsp;1 and&nbsp;2 improved the positions of the Croatian forces east and west of the Livanjsko field, and brought Bosansko Grahovo and Glamoč within striking distance. The advance secured the valley, threatened Glamoč and brought the Bosansko Grahovo-Glamoč road, the Cetina valley and the [[Vrlika]] field within Croatian artillery range.<ref>{{harvnb|Hrvatski vojnik|July 2010}}</ref> The Croatian forces sustained losses of 4 killed, 15 seriously wounded and 19 slightly injured during Operations Leap&nbsp;1 and&nbsp;2.<ref>{{harvnb|Slobodna Dalmacija|12 July 2007}}</ref>

== Aftermath ==
Gotovina said that although Operations Winter&nbsp;'94, Leap&nbsp;1 and Leap&nbsp;2 were planned and executed as three distinct operations, they represent a unified military action.<ref name=BB300/> Operation Winter&nbsp;'94 ostensibly failed to achieve its primary objective of relieving pressure on the Bihać pocket by drawing off VRS and ARSK forces to contain the attack; however, that was due to a decision by Chief of VRS General Staff General [[Ratko Mladić]] and not to mistakes in planning or execution. Faced with a choice between continuing with the attack on Bihać and blocking the advance from the Livanjsko field, the VRS chose not to move its forces, but Bihać was successfully defended by the [[V Corps (Bosnia and Herzegovina)|5th&nbsp;Corps]] of the ARBiH.<ref name=BB251/> The secondary objective of Operation Winter&nbsp;'94 was achieved more easily; the Croatian forces approached the Knin-[[Drvar]] road and directly threatened the main supply route between the Republika Srpska and the RSK capital.<ref name=BB251/> Operations Leap&nbsp;1 and&nbsp;2 built on the achievements of Operation Winter&nbsp;'94, threatened Bosansko Grahovo and created conditions to isolate Knin in [[Operation Summer&nbsp;'95]], which was executed the following month.<ref name=BB300/><ref>{{harvnb|CIA|2002|pp=364–366}}</ref> The advance was strategically significant;<ref>{{harvnb|Ripley|1999|p=86}}</ref> Mladić's decision not to react to Operation Winter&nbsp;'94 was a gamble which ultimately cost the Republika Srpska territory extending to [[Jajce]], [[Mrkonjić Grad]] and Drvar and brought about the destruction of the RSK as the advances of the Croatian forces paved the way for [[Operation Storm]].<ref>{{harvnb|Sekulić|2000|p=96}}</ref>

